79589 - ORE Rorqual The Rorqual was conceived and designed by Outer Ring Excavations in response to a growing need for capital industry platforms with the ability to support and sustain large-scale mining operations in uninhabited areas of space.

The Rorqual is notably capable of using a capital industrial core to substantially increase its industrial capabilities, while empowering its defenses during deployment in a static configuration. A key element of the industrial capacity unlocked by activating an industrial core is the ability to use compressor modules, with the Rorqual able to use the powerful and logistically impressive capital compressors. 127684 We urgently need help intercepting a group of kidnappers who just managed to snatch the niece of our CEO while she was visiting her uncle in this very system. We believe the perpetrators were a gang of mercenaries led by a felon working for an illegal organization called the Darkonnen. I'll fill you in on the details of that organization in your mission journal.

What I need you to do is capture this agent of theirs, alive if possible. We must have him here for interrogation, for we suspect he is the missing link between the kidnapping and those who are truly responsible for this heinous crime. We need to get to the bottom of which organization stands behind these grave assaults against our people. And it so happens that we know the whereabouts of a certain pirate who has had many dealings with a Darkonnen agent in the past; we hope this pirate will be able to lead you to the agent. The only catch is that he will most likely require a bit of "convincing" on your part before he parts with the needed information. I'll upload the bookmark to his location into your NeoCom; once you have extracted the information from the middleman, I expect you to find the Darkonnen agent and bring him back to me. 134268 You can make multiple consecutive jumps through stargates much more quickly manually than you can relying on Autopilot (because the Autopilot brings your ship out of warp 15 km from the stargate each time you warp, forcing you to then fly at sub-warp speed to within 2,500 m of the gate before jumping).


First, set your destination by right-clicking on the location in the journal entry or in your bookmarks. The correct stargate icon will now be highlighted in yellow, both in your overview and in space.


Now, right-click on the stargate (either in space or in the overview) and use the "Warp to within 0 km" option and then turn on Autopilot; you will drop out of warp directly beside the stargate and, because Autopilot is on, jump immediately. As soon as you begin to jump, turn your Autopilot back off; once you've jumped, simply repeat the whole "Warp to 0 km" process with each stargate along the route until you arrive at your destination system. 138980 The easiest way to travel to a destination station quickly is to use the Overview. Stargates are marked in the Overview settings panel under the "Celestial" group. Once you have selected "stargate" in the Overview settings, right-click on the hyperlinked destination system in your mission journal and choose "set destination." You will notice that the applicable stargate in your Overview is now yellow, as well as the one in space that leads to the next system along your route.


Next, simply right-click on the yellow stargate in the Overview (or in space) and hit "warp to within 0m"; turn on your Autopilot and simply sit back and relax until you are in the destination system.


Once you have arrived in the correct star system, simply right-click anywhere in space. In the drop-down window that appears, your current mission information appears at the bottom. From there, select the "dock" option and your Autopilot will bring you into the station momentarily.


Once the weapons are delivered, return to your agent's home station (also available via the drop-down simply by right-clicking anywhere in space) to collect your reward. Triglavian bioadaptive technology makes extensive use of engineered colonies of extremophilic bacteria, that are used to grow, harvest and adapt various resources found in Abyssal Deadspace. Artificial colonizing plasmids integrated into specialist tools used for direct adaptation of technology can be found in Triglavian caches in various stages of development. These mutaplasmids can be used to alter the characteristics of a wide variety of equipment types, depending on the strain and the bioadaptive tool with which they are integrated.

The mutaplasmid colony integrated into this bioadaptive tool appears to be mature and reproducing at a healthy rate. The mutational benefits and risks of using this mutaplasmid are within relatively balanced bounds. The Angel Cartel and Guristas Pirates are raiding empire space from the mysterious system of Zarzakh. In these Insurgencies, pirate aligned players are pitted against empire militias as they race to fill their pockets before the militias can destroy their Forward Operating Base.

Joining a pirate faction means dedicating yourself to the life of an outlaw. As a pirate-aligned player, you will be at war with both opposing empires, even in hisec. Alternatively, join an empire militia and fight back against the pirate insurgents, while also defending your space from the enemy empire in faction warfare. 666855 Pirates carry incursions in the warzones. Incurstions spread from the FOB. the FOB spawns randomly in a warzone system. adjacent systems then start to be corrupted. Completing pirate activities makes corruption rise and earn Pirate LP. LP can be spent in the LP stores. Pirate LP stores are found in the FOB and in Zarzakh. Pirate insurgencies begin in the warzones where continuous war has destabilized the region making systems in those regions attractive targets for pirate attacks. At the start of an insurgency, the pirate faction places an FOB in orbit around a temperate planet in the warzone and selects several systems nearby as their initial targets.

As pirate-aligned players raid these systems, they will increase the Corruption of the system. Similarly, as militia players push back against the pirate insurgents, they will increase the Suppression value of the system. As corruption is increased, the systems targeted by the pirate faction will expand to include new systems, these new systems may even include systems beyond the warzone or in high security space!

When Corruption reaches its maximum value, the system is deemed fully pillaged and the pirates score a point of progress towards their final goal. When Suppression reaches its maximum value, the system is deemed secured and the anti-pirate militia factions score a point of progress towards making the pirate Forward Operating Base (FOB) vulnerable.

If the pirates are able to fully corrupt their target number of systems before the insurgency ends then they will be victorious rewarding all contributing pirate players with a share of their spoils. This failure also weakens the FOB system, allowing the pirates to temporarily seize full control of the system removing it from Faction Warfare while their hoard is returned to their base of operations in Zarzakh. If however the FOB is destroyed before they reach their goals, the insurgency will end and the empires will reward participating militia players for their aid. During Pirate Insurgencies, pirate factions face off against the empires, each side attempting to 'score' systems by increasing the system's Corruption (pirates) or Suppression (militias) stages through the completion of various activities and objectives. As Corruption and Suppression increase in a system, they will have various effects on that system, for more details on these effects see the Corruption and Suppression section of this guide.

Insurgencies are struggles between pirates and militias with winning and losing sides. If the militias destroy the FOB before the pirates reach their goal, the empires are victorious. The FOB only becomes vulnerable once the militias have reached their goal. If the militias fail to destroy the FOB before the pirates succeed, the pirates are declared victorious. Once a victor has been declared, the insurgency will come to an end before a new insurgency begins after some time, in a new starting location.

There are two separate warzones where insurgencies may begin, one in the Caldari-Gallente warzone, where the Guristas Pirates are operating, and the other in the Amarr-Minmatar warzone, where the Angel Cartel is active. Each faction active in a warzone is at war with the other two. Guristas, Caldari and Gallente are all at war with one another, as are the Angels, Minmatar and Amarr. Pilots enlisted with any of these factions will be able to freely engage pilots aligned with those they are at war with, and will earn LP with their faction for completing insurgency activities. The Angel Cartel and Guristas Pirates have begun recruiting eggers (capsuleers) to participate in their insurgency campaigns against the empires. Pilots can enlist with one of these pirate factions to participate in insurgencies while earning valuable LP with their chosen faction.

Each pirate faction is at war with two empire factions. The Guristas are at war with the Caldari and Gallente; the Angel Cartel is at war with the Minmatar and Amarr. Joining a pirate faction will give you the freedom to shoot (and be shot by) members of the enemy empires without CONCORD interference. In addition, be aware that empire military police will attack in an enemy empire hisec system unless the insurgency has spread into it.

Both the Angels and Guristas have a minimum faction standings requirement of -2.0 for enlistment. If your standings are too low, you will be unable to enlist. As an insurgent, your enlistment may be revoked if your standings fall. Standings can be gained with these factions by completing their Epic Arc missions, allowing you a chance to repair your standings and re-enlist with the faction. 669913 Zarzakh navigation card tooltip Zarzakh is a system cloaked in the dust, gas and assorted other bits of matter that has been gravitationally captured by a black hole and is slowly orbiting closer and closer to its eventual merger with the mass singularity. The effects of orbiting in the relatively near vicinity of a black hole are already being felt in the form of intense and volatile gravitational tidal forces exerted by the singularity.

The environmental hazards of Zarzakh make it an inherently dangerous system but it is also under the control of the ruthless Deathless Circle pirate group, and is a haven for its Angel Cartel and Guristas Pirates allies. Those unfamiliar with Zarzakh's unique properties and dangers should familiarize themselves with every aspect of the system. Zarzakh is a system cloaked in the dust, gas and assorted other bits of matter that are being drawn towards the black hole known as "Point of No Return" to most of New Eden, and "Duzna Kah" to the Amarr. The location of Zarzakh places it deep in the void of Divinity's Edge, or "Yasna Zakh", and somewhat notably, essentially at the center of the New Eden cluster by virtue of the astronomical co-ordinate system used by CONCORD. Given this system was proposed by the Jove in the early days of CONCORD, it is suggestive that the dominating features of Zarzakh are the ancient Jovian gates and the ancient Jovian outpost known as "The Fulcrum".

The Zarzakh star system is wracked by severe gravitational effects rendering most locations unsafe for any ship to stop at. Safe locations are to be found at the ancient Jovian stargates, station, and shipcaster site. With these safe zones under the control of the Deathless Circle, Zarzakh is a formidable pirate haven. As a whole, the Zarzakh system is subject to an intense gravity hazard that will rapidly tear apart the hull of any spaceship experiencing the local volatile tidal forces and spacetime distortions. These damaging forces can be briefly mitigated by structural integrity systems before rapidly escalating to inevitable destruction of the vessel.

Safe Zones
Despite the forbidding dangers of the gravity hazard, a number of safe zones can be found in Zarzakh. Each of these zones is centered on ancient Jovian infrastructure that generate local protection fields around them. Safe zones are located at each of the four Jovian stargates, the Fulcrum station, and around a Jovian Observatory orbiting the star. The Deathless Shipcaster is located in the safe zone at the star.		 Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua. 674135 Pirate Insurgency Card Hint Insurgencies are dynamically generated combat zones where pilots who are aligned with a pirate faction raid systems owned by the empires. These conflicts start in low security warzone systems, but may spread to other areas of space.

Pirate-aligned pilots raid empire holdings, increasing Corruption in those systems, while militia-aligned pilots attempt to secure their space, increasing the Suppression value of systems. As Corruption and Suppression increase, they can alter the rules of space in those systems.

For a pilot who has enlisted with a pirate faction, all regions of empire space (hisec & lowsec) become areas where you and your faction allies may freely attack pilots from enemy militias without CONCORD interference. During Pirate Insurgencies, pirate factions face off against the empires, each side attempting to 'score' systems by increasing the system's Corruption (pirates) or Suppression (militias) value through the completion of various activities and objectives. Each faction has an independent target score they are looking to reach to allow them to win the insurgency, with the minimum score required to win increasing for a faction as they win multiple events.

An insurgency starts with the placement of a pirate Forward Operating Base (FOB) in the warzone. Several systems are then selected adjacent to the FOB system as initial insurgency targets. This begins the Forecasting Period'. The insurgency does not become immediately active, giving both pirate and militia capsuleers time to move ships into position and otherwise prepare themselves for the event.

Once the forecasting period ends, the main phase of the Insurgency begins. Insurgency activities begin spawning and both pirate and militia players are able to contest them. Each Insurgency activity is worth a number off Corruption or Suppression points. As pirates complete objectives they will increase the Corruption value of the system; as militia players complete insurgency activities they will increase the Suppression value of the system. A system reaching maximum Corruption scores a point for the pirates while a system reaching maximum Suppression scores a point for the empires.

When the Corruption value of a system hits stage 3 during an Insurgency event, the insurgency will spread - adding a new system to the growing insurgency zone - a new target for the pirates. Activities will begin spawning in this system immediately. This dynamic spread will prefer systems adjacent to the system which triggered the spread if possible and will not spread to systems with a security status of 0.8 and higher or 0.0 and lower.

When the pirates reach their target score they are deemed the winners of the insurgency. All systems with active insurgency will see their Corruption value increased to the next stage and the pirates will seize the FOB system as their own - removing it from the FW warzone and causing neighboring systems to become frontlines (see Factional Warfare guide for further information on frontline status). After some time, the pirates will then abandon this system, tenuously returning it to the previous owner with control at minimum and the infrastructure hub vulnerable.

If the empires reach their target score however, then the pirate FOB becomes vulnerable. The FOB has a single armor reinforcement timer and, when destroyed, will result in defeat for the pirates and victory for the empires. Following a victory by the empires, all systems in the insurgency will see their Suppression value raise by one level for some time before the event comes to a close.

There are additional rewards for players on both sides who participate in an insurgency. Participation rewards can be tracked from the insurgency window, with larger rewards paying out to players who participated on the winning faction. 696805 Upwell Fortification Bustard Upwell Fortification Variant 'Kingbird' Upwell Fortification BustaVariant 'Kingbird' Name of item 79508 (Insurgency Roaming Enforcers)
696806 Developer: Lai Dai

Deep space transports are designed with the depths of lawless space in mind. Possessing defensive capabilities far in excess of standard industrial ships, they provide great protection for whatever cargo is being transported in their massive holds. They are, however, some of the slowest ships to be found floating through space.		 Working through its member corporations within each of the "Big 4" empires, the Upwell Consortium has secured contracts to enhance counter-insurgency efforts against marauding pirate gangs and their capsuleer supporters. Analyzing the problem of responding to pirate insurgencies, taking into account lessons learned by fortification efforts during the Triglavian Invasions, the Upwell Consortium chose to source a large quantity of Bustard-class hulls from the Lai Dai corporation.

As a highly-protected but less massive hulls than the large Orca-class, the ship provided a sound basis for a variant class of fortification constructor aimed at enhancing the ability of empires to assert their sovereignty against pirate insurgents: the "Kingbird". The ship was then specially adapted to be able to deploy and service the counter-insurgency weapons platforms that are placed at strategic locations within systems where anti-pirate operations have elevated the system suppression to high levels. 697071 Corporate Outpost Raid Corporate Outpost Raid UI/Agency/PirateIncursions/Guides/Activities/ActivityNameOutpost
697074 In a corporate outpost raid activity, pirates NPCs are attacking corporate structures which are defended by Mordus Legion security forces. Players can destroy the NPCs of the opposing faction to spin down the timer in their favor - seizing control of the outpost. For pirate aligned players, no progress can be made while Mordus NPCs or empire militia pilots are guarding the facility.

Likewise, for empire-aligned militia players, no progress can be made to secure the site while pirate NPCs or pirate aligned players are within range. The timer for this site is a direct tug-of-war contest, as one side needs to wind back the progress the other has made before being able to win. Players must remain within the capture radius to make progress.		 In a corporate outpost raid activity, pirates NPCs are attacking corporate structures which are defended by Mordus Legion security forces. Players can destroy the NPCs of the opposing faction to spin down the timer in their favor - seizing control of the outpost. For pirate aligned players, no progress can be made while Mordus NPCs or empire militia pilots are guarding the facility.

Likewise, for empire-aligned militia players, no progress can be made to secure the site while pirate NPCs or pirate aligned players are within range. The timer for this site is a direct tug-of-war contest, as one side needs to wind back the progress the other has made before being able to win.
